description:
LUNCHBOX LCM's | With the girls heading back to school tomorrow, we figured it was time to whip up some lunchbox treats. Recipe below:‚Å†‚Å†
.‚Å†‚Å†
Ingredients:‚Å†‚Å†
3/4 cup @picspeanutbutter (smooth)‚Å†‚Å†
1/3 cup pure maple syrup‚Å†‚Å†
2 tablespoons virgin coconut oil‚Å†‚Å†
1 teaspoon vanilla extract‚Å†‚Å†
1/8 tsp pink Himalayan salt‚Å†‚Å†
1/3 cup desiccated coconut‚Å†‚Å†
2 scoops @happyway Vanilla Whey Protein‚Å†‚Å†
3 cups @freedomfoods Rice Puffs‚Å†‚Å†
.‚Å†‚Å†
Method:‚Å†‚Å†
1. Line an 20cm x 30cm pan with baking paper and set aside.‚Å†‚Å†
2. Place peanut butter, coconut oil, maple syrup, salt and vanilla extract into a medium pan over low heat. Stir well combined and smooth (a few minutes).‚Å†‚Å†
3.Next add in the @happyway whey powder and desiccated coconut. If the mixture feels a little thick, add in 1-2 tbs water.‚Å†‚Å†
4. Remove from heat and stir in the rice puffs. Pour into prepared pan and press the mixture flat with a spatula.‚Å†‚Å†
5. Feel free to melt some chocolate in the microwave and add to the top if you wish.‚Å†‚Å†
6. Pop the pan into the fridge for 30 minutes or until bars are completely cool. Cut into bars and enjoy!‚Å†‚Å†
.‚Å†‚Å†
* The bars can be kept in an airtight container in the fridge for up to 1 week. Take the bars out of the fridge 5 minutes before you are ready to eat them to ensure they aren't too crunchy! They will soften up at room temp. ‚Å†‚Å†
.‚Å†‚Å†

LUNCH | I'm a big fan of wraps, rolls and sandwiches. I do get a little lost for filling ideas though. This one was delicious, so I thought I'd share:‚Å†
‚Å†
1 large egg‚Å†
50g low-fat plain yoghurt‚Å†
1/2 spring onion, finely sliced‚Å†
sea salt, to taste‚Å†
ground black pepper, to taste‚Å†
2 slices rye bread (I switched to a focaccia roll)‚Å†
30g avocado‚Å†
10g light cream cheese‚Å†
1 large handful mixed lettuce leaves‚Å†
3/4 medium cucumber, sliced‚Å†
.‚Å†
1. To hard-boil the egg, place it into a small saucepan and fill with cold water until it is covered by 2cm. Bring the water to the boil over high heat. Reduce the heat ti low and simmer, covered, for 7-8 minutes. Remove the egg from the pan with a slotted spoon and place in a bowl of iced water. Leave for 1 min. Tap the egg gently on the bench to crack the shell and peel.‚Å†
.‚Å†
2. Place the egg in a small bowl and roughly mash with a fork. Add yoghurt and spring onion and mix until well combined. Season with salt and pepper, if desired.‚Å†
.‚Å†
3. To serve, place one slice of bread on a serving plate and layer the avocado, lettuce, egg mix and cucumber. Spread the cream cheese over the other slice of bread and place on top. Cut in halves or quarters and enjoy!‚Å†
.‚Å†

description:
SWEET & SOUR MANGO PORK STIR FRY  Earlier this week I posted a picture of this dish to my stories and I had quite a few people ask for the recipe. The whole family enjoyed it! Win!
.
üìùINGREDIENTS:
.
‚ú® Sauce Ingredients:
.
3 tbs rice wine vinegar
1 tbs oyster sauce
2 tbs soy sauce
3 tbs honey
1 tbs grated ginger

‚ú®Remaining Ingredients:
.
2 cloves crushed garlic
2 large carrots (sliced into half moons)
700g pork medallions (fat trimmed, sliced into thin strips)
3/4 cup orange juice
2 fresh mangos (peeled, diced)
1 spring onion (chopped)
2 tsp cornflour + 1 tbs cool water
2 tsp sesame oil
.
ü•£METHOD
.
1. In a small bowl, combine the sauce ingredients and set aside.
3. Heat the sesame oil in a wok over high heat. Add the pork and garlic along with some salt and pepper. Stir fry quickly - only for about 1 min. Add the carrots and stir for another 30 sec. Remove the pork and carrots from the heat and set aside.
4. Add the orange juice to the wok and bring to a boil. Reduce heat and allow the juice to simmer until it has reduced in volume by about half.
5. Pour the sauce mixture into the wok and simmer for a couple of minutes.
6. Add the pork and carrots back in and stir until well combined. 
7. In a cup, mix the cornflour with 1 tbs water. Add the mixture to the wok and stir until the sauce thickens.
8. Remove the wok from the heat. Stir through the mangoes until they have warmed through. 
9. Serve over rice or noodles. Sprinkle with chopped spring onion and a pinch of sesame seeds if you wish. 
.
.*TIP: The key to this dish is to cook it quickly. Resist the urge to stir fry the pork strips for longer than a minute or two in the beginning. Keep in mind that the pork will keep cooking when you add it back for re-heating at the end of the recipe. Even if the pork is initially under-cooked, it will finish cooking at the final stage.

Let‚Äôs talk about CONSISTENCY.
.
In my opinion, it‚Äôs not about doing things ‚Äòperfectly‚Äô - and as a self-proclaimed perfectionist, I can tell you this hasn‚Äôt been an easy lesson for me to learn! Ultimately, let‚Äôs strive to be more constant in our daily rituals and habits. 
.
Here are a few things I‚Äôve learned along the way:
.
‚ãí Food / Nutrition: Everybody is different. Rather than trying to perfectly adhere to someone else‚Äôs way of eating, think about the foods you enjoy. What foods make you feel great AND fuel your body‚Äôs needs? Come up with a plan to supports your unique schedule, personality and lifestyle. When you align your food with your unique preferences, you‚Äôll have a recipe for success!

‚ãí Workouts: We don‚Äôt always feel like working out. It‚Äôs easy to scroll through IG and see a bunch of people pumped up and smashing their workouts. It‚Äôs like they were BORN for it. The truth is, everyone was once a beginner and if I‚Äôm honest, I believe that most of us are inherently lazy (yes, even the IG fitspo‚Äôs).
.
I feel it‚Äôs often mind over matter. If you VALUE your health, or the example you set to your kids, or the way you feel about yourself, try to separate how you feel in the (lazy) moment and think about how you want to feel in the future. This often gives me the drive I need to persevere. 
.
Lastly, if you are getting bored, MIX IT UP. Workouts should be enjoyable but challenging, and I honestly believe it‚Äôs about finding that balance. So find something that meets you where you‚Äôre at!
.
‚ãí Planning: Spend a bit of time to plan ahead. Think of the potential obstacles that may arise. Then the potential solutions (hello, Plan B). Having some direction and clarity in what you are trying to achieve for the week can make a huge difference. It can give you a short term goal and/or mission to accomplish, along with the tools to overcome the tough times!
.
‚ãí Be Patient: Give yourself some grace. Staying the course over the long run will be more effective than micromanaging every detail and becoming so overwhelmed that it all seems too hard. Keep the bigger picture in mind and give yourself a realistic timeframe in which to achieve it.

BLUEBERRY JAM  This amazing concoction takes about 5 minutes to whip up and I promise you won‚Äôt look back! Add it to porridge, warm scones, toast or whatever else your heart desires. The whole family has approved!
.
üìù INGREDIENTS:
.
1 punnet of blueberries (200g)
1 tbs water
1/2 tbs chia seeds
1/2 - 1 tbs stevia
Squeeze of lemon juice (optional)
.
ü•£ ŒúETHOD:
.
1. Add the blueberries and water to a shallow pan and heat over a low flame.
2. Leave to simmer for 2-3 minutes. You‚Äôll see the blueberries deepen in colour and some will start to split open.
3. Remove from heat and mash with a fork until you‚Äôve achieved your desired consistency.
4. Add the chia seeds and stevia and give it all a stir. Feel free to add a squeeze of lemon juice if you prefer a bit more tanginess.
5. Pour the mixture into a jar and allow it to cool before popping it into the fridge. 
6. Leave overnight so that the chia seeds can bloat up and bring some thickness to your jam.
.
If you do make this recipe, please tag me @aprilfiit and #aprilfiitmealprep so I can re-share!
.
Happy blueberry-ing!
.
April

ü•î POTATO & LEEK SOUP  With the winter weather upon us, I found myself craving a thick, hearty soup! This quick and easy option met all expectations! Served with crusty bread and a side salad, it was perfection in a bowl. If you want a cleaner recipe than the one listed below, feel free to omit the butter and cream‚Ä¶just for the record, I didn‚Äôt. Recipe is from @taste_team.
.
üìùINGREDIENTS:
.
60 ml olive oil 
1 brown onion‚Ä®20g butter ‚Ä®2 leeks (pale section only, halved, washed, dried, thinly sliced)‚Ä®1 garlic cloves (crushed) ‚Ä®4 medium desiree potatoes (peeled, chopped into 2cm cubes)‚Ä®4 cups Massel vegetable liquid stock‚Ä®125 ml thickened cream‚Ä®2 tbs fresh chives (finely chopped) 
.
ü•£METHOD
.
1. Heat olive oil in a large saucepan over medium-high heat. Add the onion and garlic and cook, stirring, for 3 minutes or until the onion softens. Add the potato and leek and cook, stirring, for 5 minutes or until leek softens.
.
2. Add the stock and bring to the boil. Reduce heat to medium and gently boil, uncovered, for 20 minutes or until potato is soft. Remove from heat and set aside for 10 minutes to cool.
.
3. Transfer one-third of the potato mixture to the jug of a blender and blend until smooth. Transfer to a clean saucepan. Repeat in 2 more batches with the remaining potato mixture. Alternatively, use a stick blender to blend in the saucepan.
.
4. Place the soup over medium heat. Add the cream and stir to combine. Cook, stirring, for 5 minutes or until hot. Taste and season with salt.
.
5. Ladle out soup into bowls and top with fresh chives. Serve with warm, crusty bread.ü•ñ

description:
So many women I talk to tell me the same thing. They go through phases of being really good with their exercise, then fall off the bandwagon and go through extended periods of doing nothing at all. Once these times hit, it‚Äôs incredibly hard to get back into the swing of things. Trust me, I‚Äôve experienced this many times! 
.
When we become uninspired to start exercising, the motivation lacks, and deep down, there‚Äôs that guilt that we should be doing what we already know we need to do! ü§¶üèΩ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
.
The best tip I can offer (based purely on my own personal experiences), is to lower the bar. Yep! You heard me. Lower your expectations until you‚Äôve made daily exercise so easy to achieve that it‚Äôs almost laughable if you don‚Äôt manage to get it done! (Laughable for you, not others!)
.
HERE‚ÄôS THE SECRET: Let‚Äôs say for one week, you make it a goal to do just 7 min of exercise. Choose anything you want! Go for a walk, find a workout video on You Tube (dance, Pilates, HIIT, yoga etc) or follow a fitness app (if you have one!) For the second week, up it to 15min. Third week, increase to 22min and for the forth week, up your workout to 30min!
.
I find this method helpful because it gradually eases you into it. There‚Äôs no big shock to your body that ew‚Äôs you so much you never want to train again. Give yourself time and make it easy to build momentum and consistency.
.
Ideally, try to carve this ‚Äúexercise time‚Äù out at the same time every day. Perhaps that‚Äôs first thing in the morning or during the day while your baby naps. Just do your best to make it happen.
.
Within a few weeks I have no doubt you‚Äôll be back into the swing of it. You may even find that once you get started you want to move a little longer than planned.
.
Lastly, remind yourself that exercise has the potential to give you more energy than before you started. So let your body guide you and do what lights you up!

description:
‚ÄúWhat does strong look like to me?‚Äù
.
This was the question asked by @strongfitnessmag_au & @happywayau. If I‚Äôm honest, the enormity of the question left me stumped. I mean sure, the first things that come to mind are built muscles and fitness queens. But, when you really think about it, these images really only scratch the surface.
.
I feel that ‚Äústrong‚Äù refers to our physical, mental AND emotional states. Essentially, being HUMAN takes strength in itself. We FEEL so many things, THINK so many thoughts and DO so much on a daily basis.
.
In today‚Äôs day and age, it feels like we are expected to ‚Äòhave it all‚Äô. Social media leaves many of us comparing ourselves to highlight reels. Yet, so many of the women I‚Äôve spoken to mention their feelings of exhaustion and cluttered minds. As we juggle the daily responsibilities of home life, work, kids, family, relationships and the inevitable life hardships, it can feel like it‚Äôs never ending. Top that off with the pressure to keep in shape, eat well, sleep enough, be kind, be calm, practice gratitude and‚Ä¶ WAIT, STOP! Breathe.
.
THIS to me us what strong looks like. It‚Äôs in ALL the details. It‚Äôs the fact that each and every day we face things head on. We pick ourselves up and drag ourselves out of bed. We make lunches and sort kids. We play nurse when our family is sick. We are often the taxi driver to school, activities and appointments. We are the professional while at work. The counselor when times are tough. The house person for washing, cooking, groceries and cleaning. We do so much! We ARE so much. Our strength comes from DEEP within.
.
So, take a minute to pause. When you feel like you have the weight of the world on your shoulders, realise that it‚Äôs probably because we do. We are strong just for showing up each and every day. We are strong for placing one foot in front of the other. THAT is what strong looks like to me.
.

UPDATE | Hello there team! How is everyone travelling?! I can happily say that I‚Äôve made it to Day 32 of #75hard and I have ZERO regrets about starting the challenge! Never in a million years did I think I‚Äôd make it this far, but here I am! That said, I‚Äôm not even half way, so let‚Äôs not celebrate yet. üòÇü§¶üèΩ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
.
A few things I‚Äôve noticed so far:
.
üß† We can do anything we set our minds to, but it takes an honest commitment and laser sharp focus to see these plans through.
.
üìù Sometimes we need to prioritise the new habits/activities/tasks in place of other things we would normally do. For example, I would usually take a 5 minute drive to pick the girls up from school. Yesterday, I power walked to school pick up (it took 20min) and walked back home with the kids (40min). It took a little longer, but I achieved the school pick up, the outdoor walk PLUS some quality time with the fam bam. Another example, reading a book instead of scrolling on my phone, checking emails etc. Think about your daily habits and see where you can replace the not so good ones with a better choice.
.
üëäüèºRealise the value of ZERO COMPROMISE! #75HARD opened my eyes to this! How many times have you set a goal or started a program, only to find that you cut corners, and eventually fell off the band wagon? It‚Äôs human nature to make life easier, but when you give yourself zero compromise, you are forced to stick to your plan and feel so proud once your goal is achieved!
.
üèÜ Focus on maintaining momentum, small actions everyday will usually take you further than periods of intense action followed by extended breaks. As @andyfrisella once put it, ‚Äúpeople overestimate what they can achieve in 3 months and underestimate what they can achieve in 5 years‚Äù. Small daily wins people, that‚Äôs where it‚Äôs at. description:
75HARD IS COMPLETE and I STILL can‚Äôt believe I did it! üôàü•≥
.
For those that don‚Äôt know, 75HARD is a mental toughness challenge created by @andyfrisella. It claims to build confidence, self esteem, self worth, fortitude and grittiness...that is, IF you are willing to commit to the process WITHOUT COMPROMISE. I can confirm that all of the above is accurate. I am SO grateful to Andy for providing the challenge AND for offering it for FREE. #thankyou!! üôèüèº
.
At the start of this year, I wrote down the following quote:
.
‚ÄúIt‚Äôs not what you start that counts, it‚Äôs what you finish...‚Äù
.
In one of @andyfrisella‚Äôs MFCEO podcasts, he spoke about the importance of finishing things. Whether it be a book, a challenge, a business idea or something else, it‚Äôs important to see these things through to the end. That process alone will teach so many valuable lessons. If we don‚Äôt push through to the end, how can we ever truly evaluate the process and learn from the successes/failures? We need to reach a final outcome in order to reflect and then move forward.
.
I was determined to apply this to my life, as I had been feeling a little unsatisfied and unmotivated within myself. I THOUGHT about starting #75hard for months, but I was having commitment issues with it üòÇ. I was genuinely so afraid of failing it. I soon realised that not attempting it at all would be my biggest failure. So one day, I got up and thought ‚Äúlet‚Äôs just see if I can get through Day 1.‚Äù I did. Then I did it again. And again. When I reached Day 5, I realised it was time to admit to myself that I was taking it seriously. I stopped playing it down. It was not a game. I had committed myself from Day 1 and I was determined to see it through to the end.
.
There are so many things I learnt from 75hard but I will be here all night if I go into them now. I think the thing I found most surprising was how much it taught me about MYSELF. It‚Äôs honestly hard to explain. Those that have done 75hard will understand. I feel more like myself than I have in a very long time. I‚Äôm clearer about the direction I want to go in my life and I‚Äôm less afraid of my goals & dreams. ‚ú®
.

description:
I want to have a chat about TUNING IN! I get it, we all have days/weeks, where we just can‚Äôt seem to get motivated. I also know that many wise people will tell us it‚Äôs not motivation, but DISCIPLINE that keeps us going.
.
The reality is, for many of us, tapping into that discipline is half the challenge, ESPECIALLY when we‚Äôre having a crap week! üòÇ It‚Äôs easy to feel like the goals we set a few weeks back, are now a distant memory and we‚Äôre creeping back into old habits. I GET IT!
.
Toward the end of last week, I was 100% feeling like this. This week, I decided to take a week off training and I want to tell you that I had a BREAK THROUGH! But, please hear me out before you hang up your training shoes!!
.
Usually, I love to exercise. I enjoy feeling fit, strong and in momentum with my training. But every now and again, I feel completely EXHAUSTED. I‚Äôve noticed that this is a pattern for me. It happens when I‚Äôve had a few stressful weeks, there‚Äôs been a lot on my plate, and I get to a stage when I‚Äôm mentally/emotionally drained. When I give myself a break from training, I feel as though I have failed. I will fall behind on my 12 week challenge (for example) and I feel guilty that I haven‚Äôt seen my goal through. Relatable?
.
THIS TIME, I TOOK A NEW APPROACH!
.
I gave myself a week off training. I ALLOWED myself to do this, without the guilt! I told myself I needed a week of ‚Äúactive recovery‚Äù. So, I continued to wake up an hour earlier most days, but instead of training, I turned my energy inward. I used this time to listen to podcasts, read some books, journal my thoughts, practice gratitude and choose out an affirmation card each day. I was BLOWN AWAY by the result. I now feel my stress levels have reduced. I feel calm, happy and inspired again. I feel MOTIVATED.
.
So if you‚Äôre feeling off, TUNE IN! What is it that you need? Sometimes it‚Äôs intense workouts, and other times it‚Äôs growth in other areas. I‚Äôm not saying throw in the towel. I‚Äôm just saying that you‚Äôre allowed to TUNE IN!
.
That said, I‚Äôm off to the gym! This girl is back to her usual self again! Happy Friday!
.

description:
Here is a favourite recipe of mine! This takes me less than 10min to prep and is SO delicious! The trick is to chop all the salad ingredients in a food processor (if available), which combines all the ingredients into a beautiful crunchy texture within seconds. I hope you all like it!
.
Rainbow Salad
.
Salad Ingredients:
.
1 carrot (chopped into quarters)
1/4 of a whole fresh beetroot
2 cups baby spinach leaves
1/4 of small red onion
2 tbs fresh parsley
.
Topping Ingredients:
.
1 small tin tuna (in extra virgin olive oil)
1/4 of an avocado (diced)
1/3 cup pomegranate kernels 
Salt
Pepper
Lemon Juice
.
Method:
.
1. Throw all of the salad ingredients into a food processor* and pulse until everything is finely chopped. Keep a close watch, as this usually only takes about 5 seconds! .
2. Top salad with tuna, avocado and pomegranate.
.
3. Season with salt, pepper and lemon juice to taste.
.
*If you do not have a food processor, you could finely dice or grate these ingredients to achieve a similar texture.
.
Have a lovely weekend babes!!
